How are we to estimate these speculations? It is obvious in the first place that they stand in marked opposition to, or at least in distinction from, theories current among Bacou's contemporaries. To judge rightly of them we must bear in mind that throughout the greater part of the thirteenth century questions were being agitated of even greater impor- tance than the controversy between realism and nominalism. The pantheistic tendencies discernible in Averroes and other Arabian thinkers had been diffused, as we have seen, by men like Arnaury and David of Dinant They were responsible, as some thought, for the disastrous anarchy which early in the century had devastated southern F rance. Bacon was quick to perceive the danger of maintaining the unity of matter. It had been defended, as he points out (Op. Maj. Ι vol. i. p. 144), by passages from Aristotle which he wishes to believe had been badly translated.
